{The main thing to note here is that the black king is tied down. With the white pawn on a7, say, Black's king can't step on the f-file due to the trick shown in variation X. Hence, in the current position, the black king can never step on the e-file, crossing over the f-file, due to a6-a7, invoking the same trick. White, on the other hand, has a very simple plan: they want to get their king to a7 and release the rook; we have seen in the previous example how that position wins for White. Since the black king is confined to f- to h-files, it can't stop White from realising this idea; this is where the Vancura trick comes in. [#]} 1... Rf1+ ({Variation X:} 1... Ra2 2. a7 {in this position bringing the king to the f-file is a mistake.} Kf7 $4 3. Rh8 $1 {threatening a8=Q} Rxa7 4. Rh7+ $18) 2. Ke4 Rf6 $3 {the thematic Vancura move. Now Black draws because if the wK moves towards a7, the black rook can start checking it from the side, and if White goes a6-a7, Black has Ra6.} 3. Ke5 Rc6 4. Ra7+ Kg6 5. Kd5 Rf6 $11 1/2-1/2

