{[#] Before this penultimate round six players were jointly leading with 6/7. I was paired on top board with Vallejo as black.} 54. Kxg5 {Chess is a tough game and rook pawn endgames can be specially the most difficult part. Luckily here my pieces are perfectly placed. Also I knew about the game Sasi - Aronian, World Team 2010 when Sasi won on top board and I was playing on board 3. We had a very close look on this endgame then. Those who haven't seen that I suggest to have a look at that game then my ending will look trivial :)} Rg8+ {The difference with Sasi - Aronian is that here white's rook is placed on e4 instead of e3 which makes my move (Rg8) possible and not a losing move like in Sasi - Aronian.} (54... Kd5 {Just as an example how tricky these endgame could be...apart from the move that I played in the game and this one which has similar idea everything else loses!}) 55. Kh4 Rh8+ 56. Kg4 Rg8+ 57. Kh4 Rh8+ 58. Kg4 Rg8+ 59. Kh3 Rh8+ 60. Kg2 Kd5 {one of easy way to remember this endgame is almost always king is ideally placed on d6 and d5 making sure that white will not have enough time to protect the pawn with his rook (Rook on e4/ e3 and pawn on g4/g3) in order to advance with his king as black's active king will attack the rook which wont be able to do both cutting of black king and protecting the 'g' pawn at the same time.} (60... Kd7 {this is also good enough in this particular position. However, I knew my defensive method and wanted to stick to it.} 61. Kf3 Rf8+ 62. Rf4) 61. Re7 Rg8 {Black maintains his ideally placed position. At this stage a number of moves holds.} 62. Re1 Kd4 63. Re6 Kd5 64. Re2 Kd4 (64... Kd6 65. Re3 Kd5) 65. Re7 Kd5 66. Kf3 Rf8+ 67. Ke2 Rg8 68. Re3 Kd4 69. Kf2 Rf8+ {This expedites the outcome but on the process black has to make some only moves which I was confident about.} (69... Kd5 {was easiest if one doesn't want to calculate forced lines.} 70. Kf3 Rf8+ $11) 70. Rf3 Rg8 71. Rf5 Ke4 {first only move} 72. Rh5 Rf8+ $1 {second} 73. 